              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3nc5sv7p/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>at night and being dead the next morning <add>עליו השלום</add></p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">News from here there is but little more than you\n                                        have<lb/> been supplied with. Synagogue was more than\n                                        usually<lb/> full these holidays. Indeed I have never seen\n                                        it so full<lb/> since I have been here. If you think it\n                                        worth noticing<lb/> in the Occident I send you a report or\n                                        rather some “facts”<lb/> relating to my<add>?</add> lecture\n                                        at the Mechaim's Institute of this place.<lb/> On\n                                                  <date>Tuesday evng 27 March</date> I\n                                        gave—according to the promise<lb/> made to the gents of the\n                                        committee while <add>ר' ניסים</add> was here—a<lb/> second\n                                        lecture in the Odd Fellows Hall on the present state<lb/> of\n                                        the Jews &amp; Christians in the dominions of the\n                                                  <persName>Shah</persName>. There was<lb/> an\n                                        unusually large audience to hear me—Indeed the<lb/> subject\n                                        appears to have pleased the fancy of the Montreallers<lb/>\n                                        very much, since they came so <add>?</add> to hear\n                                        about<lb/> the countrymen of <persName>R Nifrim</persName>,\n                                        not withstanding that lectures so<lb/> late in the season\n                                        are (mirabile dictu!) rather thinly attended,<lb/> as if\n                                        there should be “a season” for having lectures too. On<lb/>\n                                        being introduced by the President I was very favorably\n                                        received<lb/> and judging from the applause, cries of\n                                        “shame” slight groans<lb/> &amp;tc the lecture appeared to\n                                        have engaged their entire sympathies<lb/> I commenced by\n                                        expatiating on the “twice blest quality of <add>?</add><lb/>\n                                        and alluded to the generous sympathy shown to the\n                                        stranger<lb/> Israelite from <placeName>Persia</placeName>\n                                        who lately visited this city, which I said was<lb/> a proof\n                                        that charity had no regard to call color country or\n                                        creed<lb/> but was universal as it was it was twice on the\n                                        usefulness<lb/> of such institutions as the one I addressed\n                                        I proceeded to describe<lb/> more particularly the dress\n                                        manner of education, marriages,</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3nc5sv7p/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
